# Accessibility Rules

Accessibility is part of code quality, not a final polish pass. Apply these rules to user-facing UI changes and mention relevant accessibility verification in the final response.

---

## 1) Semantic Structure

- Prefer semantic HTML over generic containers.
- Use landmarks such as `<header>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<aside>`, and `<footer>` when they match the content.
- Keep heading levels meaningful and ordered.
- Prefer native controls such as `<button>`, `<a>`, `<input>`, `<select>`, and `<textarea>` before custom interactive elements.
- Do not add ARIA when native HTML already provides the right role, name, state, and behavior.

```tsx
// Good
<button type="button" onClick={onClose}>
	Close
</button>

// Avoid
<div onClick={onClose}>Close</div>
```

---

## 2) Names, Labels, and Descriptions

- Every interactive control needs an accessible name.
- Icon-only buttons must have an `aria-label` or equivalent visible label.
- Form inputs need associated labels using `<label htmlFor>` or an equivalent accessible pattern.
- Use `aria-describedby` for helper text, constraints, and error descriptions.
- Mark invalid fields with `aria-invalid` and connect the error message to the field.
- Informative images need meaningful `alt` text; decorative images should use empty `alt=""`.

```tsx
// Good
<button type="button" aria-label="Close dialog">
	<CloseIcon aria-hidden="true" />
</button>

<label htmlFor="email">Email</label>
<input id="email" aria-invalid={hasError} aria-describedby={hasError ? 'email-error' : undefined} />
{hasError ? <p id="email-error">Enter a valid email address.</p> : null}
```

---

## 3) Keyboard and Focus

- All interactive behavior must be reachable and operable by keyboard.
- Preserve visible focus indicators.
- Keep tab order predictable and aligned with the visual and logical flow.
- Manage focus for dialogs, popovers, menus, validation errors, routed views, and async updates.
- Escape should close dismissible overlays when that is the expected platform behavior.
- Avoid keyboard traps unless the UI is an active modal that intentionally contains focus.

---

## 4) State and Announcements

- Loading, success, error, and status changes must be available to assistive technology when they are not visually persistent.
- Use live regions or status elements for important async changes.
- Disabled controls should communicate why an action is unavailable when the reason is not obvious.
- Empty, loading, error, and success states should preserve semantic structure and focus behavior.

---

## 5) Visual Accessibility

- Meet WCAG AA contrast for text and meaningful UI indicators.
- Do not rely on color alone to communicate state, errors, categories, or progress.
- Check contrast for text, icons, focus rings, borders that convey state, and disabled-but-readable content.
- Keep touch and pointer targets large enough to use reliably.
- Ensure text, controls, and interactive targets remain usable across responsive layouts and browser zoom.
- Respect reduced-motion preferences for non-essential animation.

---

## 6) Verification

- For UI changes, verify keyboard navigation through the changed flow.
- Check focus entry, focus movement, and focus return for overlays and routed changes.
- Confirm accessible names for icon-only controls and custom widgets.
- Confirm labels, helper text, and error messages for forms.
- Mention any manual accessibility checks that were not run.
